      "label": "Transcript",
      "value": "[Page One]\nWashington\n16th Decr. [December] 1847\nMy dear sir,\nWhen I parted with you \nand other friends in Charleston, I hoped \nto be able, in a short time, to inform \nyou what would be the probable direction, \nwhich events would take in reference \nto the great questions, which now agitate \nthe country; but I regret to say, that I \nhave, as yet been able to form no de-\nfinite opinion. I have, however, seen \nenough to satisfy me, that we have much \nto fear and little to hope, in reference either \nto the abolition, or Mexican question. I fear \nthat even the South will be fatally di-\nvided in reference to the former. You\nhave of course seen the [illegible] this of \nMr. Dickenson. They, I doubt not, origin-\nnate with the administration, and are \nintended to cover both questions, but more \nespecially the abolition, and to form a \n[illegible] point around, which the whole de-\nmocratick party may rally.  Much [illegible] \n[location?] is used, in order to disguise \ntheir real meaning, but their real object \n[Page Two]\nis to affirm, that the [territorial?] [legislatures?] may \nexclude the introduction of slaves, while \nthey deny that Congress can. The plain \nintent, taking the two [solutions?] together, \nis, to erect whatever part of Mexico \nwe may acquire, or choose to take \ninto territories and let the people of \nthe territories, Mexicans and all, \ndecide whether slavery shall be ex-\ncluded or not. Now, when we [accept?] \nthat the Mexicans are all abolitionists, it \nis easy to see, that the scheme will, or ef-\nfectively exclude slavery, as would \nthe [Wilmot?] [illegible]. Indeed, I \nwould rather concede to Congress the \nright of deciding whether slavery should \nor should not exist in a territory, \nthan to leave it to the Mexicans to \ndecide. In the one case, we would \nat least have some control; but \nin the other none; and yet there are \nSouthern men, who I fear will be either \ntoo blind to see the truth, or too much \ndevoted to party and President making \nto act on it.\n[Page Three]\nSuch a state of things is clearly shown, that \nas [illegible] such as we [propose?] is indispensible \nhere; but at the same time, I regret \nto say, that I, as yet, see no prospect \nof any cooperation from any other Southern \nState, in the way of friends, or even \nsympathy with such a [illegible]. It \nwould be, if established now, a \nCarolinian [illegible], which, \nI fear, would very greatly diminish \nits usefulness. Their thinking, my im-\npression is, that it would not be ad-\nvisable to establish it yet. It may be \nthat the farther development of \nthe [illegible] will [bring?] the South more \ntogether, when it may be established \nwith advantage. I will keep my at-\ntention directed towards it. \nAs to the Mexican War, the great danger \nis, that it will terminate in leaving no choice \nbut to hold it as a conquered Province, \nor incorporate it in the Union. I have \nmoved on the subject to \nbring the danger to the [illegible] of the people and \n[Page Four]\nthe government, with all the calamities to which \nit will exp[illegible] [us?], so that they may deliberately \ndecide with their eyes open, \nwhether they will persist in a course \nof policy, which must lead to such \nresults, or not. In making the movement, \nI have changed no opinion, or views \nwhich I have heretofore entertained \nor [illegible]. The future is as uncertain \nand [illegible], as it was the day the War \nwas declared. What will be the end \nno one can tell, but let what will come \nI shall do my duty.\nAs to the remaining question, the Presidential \nelection, the indications are strongly in favor \nof General Taylor. The Whigs, I do not think \nwill [illegible] Clay. Indeed, the Southern Whigs \ncannot; and they will I think, rally to a \nman [around?] Taylor. I [illegible] nothing \n[illegible] as to his opinion; but the \n[illegible] is strong that he will be with \nus on the question of the [illegible], [illegible] \nand the Tariff of ’46.\nShow this to [illegible], [illegible] and other friends. \nI cannot write to all, and I hope that \n[Page Five]\na letter to one will be regarded as to \nall. \nI shall take up my resolutions after the \nholy days. I hope our papers will \ncome out against Dickenson’s resolutions; and \nthat [illegible] able [person?] will expose them \nin the Mercury. Should they be adopted \nour situation will be more critical \nthan it ever has been. The resolutions \n[illegible] [illegible] by the [Senate?] of [illegible] \nare well drawn up and the second [directly?]\n[illegible] his, as far as territories are con-\ncerned.\nYours truly\nJ.[John] C.[Caldwell] Calhoun\nH.[Henry] W.[Workman] Conner Sr."
